Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# Function to plot histograms and boxplots for all numerical variables in the columns present in the data set
def plot_numerical_variable(column_name):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 5))
    
    # Histogram with color palette
    sns.histplot(df[column_name], bins=10, kde=True, ax=ax[0], color='dodgerblue')
    ax[0].set_title(f'Histogram of {column_name}')
    
    # Boxplot with color palette
    sns.boxplot(x=df[column_name], ax=ax[1], color='lightcoral')
    ax[1].set_title(f'Boxplot of {column_name}')
    
    plt.show()
In [14]:
# Function to plot countplots for categorical variables
def plot_categorical_variable(column_name, threshold):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    
    # Create the countplot with color palette
    ax = sns.countplot(
        y=df[column_name], 
        order=df[column_name].value_counts().index,
        palette='viridis'
    )
    
    # Get the y-tick labels
    # y-ticks determines the postions of the labels present
    #y-ticklables are the labels present in the y-axis
    # here only y-axis is formatted since it is a count plot and x-axis is only the count or frequecy of the column, where as the y is the column name
    y_ticks = ax.get_yticks()
    y_labels = [item.get_text() for item in ax.get_yticklabels()]
    
    # Modify y-tick labels to show every 10th label
    new_labels = [
        label if (i % threshold == 0) else '' 
        for i, label in enumerate(y_labels)
    ]
    
    # Set the new y-tick labels
    ax.set_yticklabels(new_labels)
    
    plt.title(f'Countplot of {column_name}')
    plt.show()

def plot_top_n_customers(column_name, top_n=10):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    
    # Get the top N most frequent customer IDs( here N is 10 by default)
    top_n_values = df[column_name].value_counts().nlargest(top_n).index
    
    # Filter the DataFrame to include only these top N customers
    filtered_df = df[df[column_name].isin(top_n_values)]
    
    # Create the countplot
    ax = sns.countplot(
        y=filtered_df[column_name], 
        order=filtered_df[column_name].value_counts().index,
        palette='viridis'
    )
    
    # Get the y-tick labels
    y_ticks = ax.get_yticks()
    y_labels = [item.get_text() for item in ax.get_yticklabels()]

    
    # Set the new y-tick labels
    ax.set_yticklabels(y_labels)
    
    plt.title(f'Countplot of Top {top_n} {column_name}')
    plt.show()

# Call the function with customer_id and display the top 20 customers
plot_top_n_customers('customer_id', top_n=20)

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

In [32]:
df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df['rating'], errors='coerce')

# Drop rows with NaN values in the 'rating' column
df_rating = df.dropna(subset=['rating'])

# Group by restaurant_name to get the rating count and average rating
restaurant_ratings = df_rating.groupby('restaurant_name').agg(
    rating_count=('rating', 'size'),
    average_rating=('rating', 'mean')
).reset_index()

# Filter restaurants based on the conditions
eligible_restaurants = restaurant_ratings[
    (restaurant_ratings['rating_count'] > 50) &
    (restaurant_ratings['average_rating'] > 4)
]
eligible_restaurants.sort_values(by="rating_count", ascending=False)

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [33]:
def calculate_commission(cost):
    if cost > 20:
        return cost * 0.25
    elif cost > 5:
        return cost * 0.15
    else:
        return 0

# Apply the function to the 'cost_of_the_order' column to calculate the revenue for each order
df['revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_commission)

# Sum up the revenue to get the total net revenue
print(f"Total revenue generated: ${df['revenue'].sum()}")

Total revenue generated: $6166.303

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

This report provides a comprehensive analysis of FoodHub's performance metrics, focusing on aspects such as restaurant popularity, food preparation time, order costs, delivery efficiency, and customer satisfaction. The data highlights Shake Shack as the most popular restaurant, indicates consistent demand, and suggests areas for improvement in delivery times and customer engagement. Key findings and recommendations are presented to enhance service quality and customer satisfaction, supporting strategic business decisions for FoodHub.

Restaurant Popularity and Demand¶

Shake Shack's Dominance¶

Shake Shack emerges as the most popular restaurant during both weekdays and weekends. This consistent demand underscores the brand's strong market presence and customer preference.

Other Popular Restaurants¶

In addition to Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop and Blue Ribbon Sushi are also frequently ordered from and highly rated. Promoting these restaurants can attract more customers and enhance brand loyalty.

Average Food Preparation Time¶

Preparation Time Analysis¶

The average food preparation time across all restaurants is approximately 27.37 minutes. This time frame aligns with industry standards, balancing the need for quality preparation with efficient service delivery.

Correlation with Order Costs¶

A correlation coefficient of 0.042 indicates a very weak positive correlation between the cost of the order and food preparation time. This suggests that higher-priced orders take slightly longer to prepare, but the impact is negligible.

Order Costs¶

Distribution of Order Costs¶

Approximately 29.24% of orders cost over $20. This significant portion of high-cost orders reflects a customer base willing to pay for premium menu items, indicating potential for revenue growth through dynamic pricing strategies.

Correlation with Delivery Time¶

The correlation coefficient of -0.03 between order cost and delivery time suggests a very weak negative correlation. This implies that higher-cost orders are slightly associated with shorter delivery times, but the effect is almost negligible.

Delivery Times¶

Delivery time ranges from approximately 15 to 32.5 minutes. This suggests that most orders are delivered within this timeframe, regardless of the type of cuisine.

General Delivery Efficiency¶

The mean order delivery time is 24.16 minutes. While generally acceptable, 10.54% of orders exceed 60 minutes, negatively impacting customer satisfaction.

Weekday vs. Weekend Delivery Times¶

Delivery times are longer on weekdays (28.34 minutes) compared to weekends (22.47 minutes). Increased traffic or higher order volumes during the week likely contribute to this discrepancy.

Correlation with Preparation Time¶

A correlation coefficient of 0.011 indicates an extremely weak positive correlation between food preparation time and delivery time, suggesting minimal impact of preparation duration on overall delivery efficiency.

Customer Ratings¶

Rating Distribution¶

Customer ratings range from 3.0 to 5.0, with most ratings on the higher end, indicating general satisfaction. However, the presence of significant peaks at ratings of 3.0 and 5.0 suggests variability in customer experiences.

Factors Influencing Ratings¶

The data does not show a clear correlation between customer ratings and variables like order cost or delivery time. This implies that other factors, such as food quality and customer service, play a more significant role in determining satisfaction.

Cuisine Types¶

Variety and Popularity¶

FoodHub offers a wide variety of cuisines, including American, Indian, Japanese, Mediterranean, Italian, Chinese, French, Mexican, Korean, Middle Eastern, Southern, Thai, Vietnamese, and Spanish. American cuisine is the most popular, followed by Japanese and Italian.

Delivery Efficiency Across Cuisines¶

There is no significant difference in delivery times or customer ratings across different cuisine types, suggesting consistent delivery efficiency and satisfaction regardless of the cuisine.

Delivery Time Distribution¶

Distribution Range¶

Delivery times range from approximately 15 to 32.5 minutes, with a peak around 25 minutes, indicating efficient delivery for most orders. However, the outliers taking over 60 minutes require attention.

Cost Variation: Cost of Orders by Cuisine: The cost of orders varies significantly across different cuisines. For instance, Japanese cuisine appears to have a higher median cost compared to other cuisines on both weekdays and weekends. This could be due to the quality of ingredients used, the complexity of preparation, or the premium nature of Japanese cuisine. Day of the Week: The graph indicates that there is a wider rang e in order costs during weekends for most cuisines compared to weekdays. This could be due to increased demand or special weekend menus offered by restaurants.

Outliers: There are several outliers in the data, particularly for Japanese, Mexican, and American cuisines. These could represent special dishes or large group orders that are priced higher than typical meals.

Variation in Delivery Time by Cuisine Type: The graph shows that the average delivery time varies by cuisine type. Some cuisines, such as Korean and Japanese, have shorter average delivery times, while others, like French and Spanish, have longer average delivery times. This could be due to factors like the complexity of preparing the dishes, the efficiency of the restaurants, or the availability of delivery personnel familiar with the routes to these restaurants.

Difference in Delivery Time Between Weekday and Weekend: For each cuisine type, there is a slight difference in the average delivery time between weekdays and weekends. This could be due to factors like increased order volume during weekends or different traffic conditions affecting delivery times.

Overall Trend: Despite the variations, the overall trend suggests that the average delivery time is under 35 minutes for all cuisine types on both weekdays and weekends. This indicates that the food aggregator company is maintaining a reasonable delivery time across all cuisines and days of the week.

In summary, the cost of the order, food preparation time, and delivery time are largely independent of each other according to this data. This could imply that the efficiency of the restaurant’s food preparation and the delivery service are not significantly impacted by the cost of the orders. However, it’s important to note that correlation does not imply causation, and these findings should be further investigated with more rigorous statistical testing.

While the swarm plot provides a useful overview of the distribution of customer ratings and delivery times across different cuisine types, it does not provide clear insights into the factors that influence these variables. Further analysis could involve exploring the relationship between these variables and other factors such as cost of the order, day of the week, and food preparation time. This would provide a more comprehensive understanding of the factors that influence customer satisfaction and help the company make data-driven decisions to improve their service.

This analysis can help the company in understanding the factors affecting their service and in making data-driven decisions to improve their business. They might focus on improving their app’s user interface or expanding their restaurant partnerships, as these areas are not directly tied to the cost of orders or delivery times. Consider conducting customer surveys to gather more data on customer preferences and satisfaction levels.

Recommendations:¶

Improve Delivery Efficiency Promote High-Rated Restaurants Encourage Customer Ratings Implement Dynamic Pricing Enhance Customer Engagement

To enhance delivery efficiency, particularly for the 10.54% of orders taking over an hour, FoodHub should optimize delivery routes and increase delivery personnel during peak times. If a particular cuisine type consistently has longer delivery times, the company might investigate the reasons and work with the restaurants to improve their preparation or handling times. Understanding the difference in delivery times between weekdays and weekends can help in better planning and resource allocation.

Promoting highly rated and frequently ordered restaurants such as Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop, and Blue Ribbon Sushi can attract more customers and leverage their popularity.

To improve customer engagement, especially for those who order infrequently, FoodHub could conduct surveys or direct communication to understand their preferences and address any barriers to more frequent use. With 736 unrated orders, offering incentives like discounts or loyalty points for customer ratings can gather more data for service improvement.

Introducing dynamic pricing or premium menu items, given the significant portion of orders exceeding $20, can boost revenue and cater to customers willing to pay for premium experiences.
